summary: 06/10/1999: A bomb planted under a car owned by Pear Vali, the CEO of the Artmiks Advertising Agency, exploded in the early hours of the morning in Tallinn, Estonia. Fatherland claimed responsibility for the explosion, stating that it was angered by western influences communicated through advertising, which threatened to repress Estonia's national culture. No casualties were reported incident, but the explosion shattered windows and damaged cars nearby.
target1: The car of Artmiks advertising agency CEO, Pear Vali
motive: In reaction to what the group believed to be western influences communicated through advertising, which threatened to repress Estonia's national culture.
propcomment: Nearby windows and cars were damaged.
scite1: "Bomb Attack on Estonian Ad Industry," RDS Business & Industry Selected Documents, June 18, 1999.
scite2: "Bomb Explodes in Central Tallinn Early in Thursday," Baltic News Service, June 10, 1999.

location: In the car outside of his suburban home in the Parita-Merivalja district
summary: 03/10/2001: The head executive of a Russian newspaper, Vitali Haitov, was shot and killed outside of his home in Tallinn, Parita-Merivalja district, Estonia around 3:30pm.  The shooter was not identified and no group claimed responsibility.
target1: Vitali Haitov, owner of the Estoniya daily newspaper and publisher of the Vesti Nedelya Plus weekly newspaper
motive: Although the specific motive was unknown, sources suggested that this attack was related to the killing of Haitov's son a year before (possibly due to some questionable business dealings by Haitov), and a possible subsequent private investigation led by Haitov.  Sources also suggest that rival gangs may be responsible as several other deaths in the area had been blamed upon them as well.
addnotes: The murder was called in to the police at 3:37pm.  The shooter also killed Haitov's Rottweiler, which had been outside at the time.  Sources note that Haitov's grandson, who was eight, witnessed the shooting.
scite1: Michael Tarm, "Publisher of Russian-language newspaper shot dead," Associated Press, March 10, 2001.
scite2: "Publisher of Estonia's Russian-language daily shot dead," Baltic News Service (BNS), March 10, 2001.
scite3: Olga Yakovleva, "Publisher of Estoniya Russian-Language Newspaper killed in Tallinn," Nezavisimaya Gazeta, March 12, 2001.

location: The attack occurred near the Defence Minstry in Tallinn, Estonia, Estonia.
summary: 08/11/2011: On Thursday afternoon around 1500, in Tallinn, Estonia, Estonia, a civilian, identified as Karen Drambjan, fired shots and detonated a smoke bomb at the Defense Ministry. Later, police moved in and killed the gunman. No casualties or damages were reported in the attack and no group claimed responsibility.
motive: The specific motive for the attack is unknown.
weapdetail: Unknown firearms and a smoke bomb were used in the attack.
scite1: Reuters, "Gunman Killed after Estonian Ministry Shooting," Reuters, August 11, 2011, http://www.trust.org/alertnet/news/gunman-killed-after-estonian-ministry-shooting/.
scite2: Matt Clements, "Gunman Opens Fire at Estonian Defence Ministry," LexisNexis Academic, World Markets Research Centre, August 12, 2011.
scite3: Jari Tanner, "Gunman Killed after Attacking Estonian Ministry," LexisNexis Academic, Assocaited Press, August 11, 2011.

summary: 09/03/2015: Assailants set fire to an asylum seekers' center in Vao village, Laane-Viru county, Estonia. No one was injured, but the center was slightly damaged in the blaze. No group claimed responsibility for the incident.
motive: The specific motive is unknown; however, sources suspected that the attack was related to Estonia's resettlement policy of refugees.
propcomment: An asylum center building was damaged in this attack.
scite1: "Center for asylum seekers set on fire in Estonia," Xinhua General News Service, September 3, 2015.
scite2: "Roivas demands zero tolerance on Vao arson," ERR News, September 3, 2015.
scite3: "Immigration center in Estonia set ablaze on Thursday morning - The Baltic Times," Baltic Times, September 3, 2015.

location: The incident occurred at a parking lot in Parnu Maantee.
summary: 12/18/2015: An explosives-laden vehicle detonated in a parking lot in Tallinn, Harju, Estonia. There were no reported casualties resulting from the blast. No group claimed responsibility for the incident.
targsubtype1_txt: Public Area (garden, parking lot, garage, beach, public building, camp)
